320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c12"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpin"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Industry News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c182"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c16"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c12"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:cdiv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">M/MENT N/BCY N/CAC N/CRM N/DVT N/GEN N/LWS R/NME R/US WSTN.XX </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday Lantern Capital PE RESTRUCTURING SB102607501860207548610045841140513203310921 Burkle, Ron Contreras-Sweet, Maria Weinstein, Bob Weinstein, Harvey PRO SYND Private Equity WSJ-PRO-PE CODES_REVIEWED Media entertainment DEBTMEDIA Northeast US DEBTNORTHEASTUS PEMEDIAENTERTAINMENT North America PEREGIONSNORTHAMERICA Business </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OUSB </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Business</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Victims' Lawyer Pushes Back on Fast Sale of Weinstein Co. Hollywood studio is looking to complete a chapter 11 sale in less than two months</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>An attempt to quickly sell Weinstein Co. assets in bankruptcy is facing pushback over how lawsuits pending against the company will be handled.</Para><Para>The troubled TV and film studio <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weinstein-co-to-file-for-bankruptcy-as-part-of-deal-with-lantern-capital-1521513365">filed for chapter 11</ELink> protection late Monday in Delaware with a deal in hand to sell its assets to investment firm Lantern Capital for $310 million, subject to better offers in a potential bankruptcy auction. Weinstein Co. advisers want a judge to approve a sale <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://pdf.courtdrive.com/pacer/debke/172504/dockets/10.00000/1-BFC2CD2A-2C51-11E8-A66A-31DFD686BC55">by May 4</ELink>, court papers say.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>A lawyer who represents a group of women who have sued the entertainment company over sexual assaults and sexual harassment allegedly committed by co-founder Harvey Weinstein said the process proposed by Lantern and Weinstein Co. won't provide for "a proper evaluation" of the studio or a determination of whether the sale is in the best interest of creditors. That includes those with pending suits against the company.</Para><Para>"There is nothing in these sale documents that purports to provide any fund or compensation for the victims," said Cris Armenta in an interview with The Wall Street Journal. She is part of a team of lawyers representing six actresses in a proposed class action against Weinstein Co., Harvey Weinstein and current and former members of the entertainment company's board of directors.</Para><Para>The studio is seeking to set an April 30 deadline for bids to top Lantern's offer and a May 2 auction, if any competing bids come in. Lantern has also agreed to take on more than $125 million in project-level debt as part of its deal.</Para><Para>Sale timelines are often the first scrimmage line for companies and creditors in chapter 11, with companies and buyers pushing for speed, and creditors insisting that more time and money be spent to make sure the best deal is put on the table. That could be crucial <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weinstein-co-bankruptcy-likely-to-shortchange-alleged-victims-1520454348">to hopes of recovery</ELink> for women who, in at least nine lawsuits, accuse the Weinstein Co. and its leaders of negligence in failing to rein in Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct.</Para><Para>Weinstein Co. advisers defended the expedited sale process, saying in a court filing that they engaged in extensive marketing before filing bankruptcy and that a speedy sale will best preserve the value of the company for stakeholders</Para><Para>As part of the bankruptcy, Weinstein Co. also announced it would release from nondisclosure agreements, or NDAs, individuals who allegedly suffered or witnessed sexual misconduct by Mr. Weinstein. Mr. Weinstein has admitted mistakes but denied allegations of nonconsensual sex.</Para><Para>Representatives for Weinstein Co. didn't immediately return messages Tuesday seeking comment. The board said in a statement Monday that "no one should be afraid to speak out or coerced to stay quiet."</Para><Para>Some plaintiffs' lawyers welcomed the move, saying that lifting the NDAs could support legal action against current or former members of the Weinstein Co. board, though clarification on the actual scope of the announcement is needed.</Para><Para>"Potentially, it opens the floodgates of information," said Jeff Herman, a lawyer who is representing actress Kadian Noble and Dominique Huett in sexual assault and harassment complaints pending against the studio, Harvey Weinstein, and his brother and company chairman Bob Weinstein.</Para><Para>Ms. Armenta said it is unclear, however, if the releases would apply to Weinstein Co. employees and alleged victims or if the releases would have any impact on nondisclosure agreements reportedly entered into between Harvey Weinstein alone and another individual.</Para><Para>"We don't know what the legal significance of that statement is or if it has legal significance at all," Ms. Armenta said.</Para><Para>Harvey Weinstein was fired by the Weinstein Co. board in October after allegations against him were first reported. Mr. Weinstein, and current and former members of Weinstein Co.'s board of directors have sought to dismiss the class-action complaint. Bankruptcy halts lawsuits that have been brought against companies but does not stop the prosecution of claims against individual board members or Mr. Weinstein.</Para><Para>Lantern had been backing a proposed deal to acquire the entertainment company outside of chapter 11 as part of a buyers group lead by businesswoman Maria Contreras-Sweet and investor Ron Burkle but the transaction fell apart twice before the bankruptcy. That offer was valued at $500 million and <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/potential-weinstein-co-sale-structure-stokes-victim-concerns-1516110260">proposed creating a fund for victims</ELink> of alleged sexual harassment and assault by Mr. Weinstein.</Para><Para>Write to Jonathan Randles at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:Jonathan.Randles@wsj.com">Jonathan.Randles@wsj.com</ELink> and Peg Brickley at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:peg.brickley@wsj.com">peg.brickley@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>For related coverage</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weinstein-co-to-file-for-bankruptcy-as-part-of-deal-with-lantern-capital-1521513365">Weinstein Co. Files for Bankruptcy as Part of Deal With Lantern Capital</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weinstein-co-bankruptcy-likely-to-shortchange-alleged-victims-1520454348">Weinstein Co. Bankruptcy Likely to Shortchange Alleged Victims</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/potential-weinstein-co-sale-structure-stokes-victim-concerns-1516110260">Potential Weinstein Co. Sale Structure Stokes Concerns of Accuser Advocates</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Jonathan Randles and Peg Brickley </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/victims-lawyer-pushes-back-on-fast-sale-of-weinstein-co-1521624601" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

